y critics have argued, this political conversion did not divide the writer into an irreconcilable before and after - the apolitical versus the political - but rather it simply shifted the emphasis of the representation of the political that already existed in Cortázar's writings.Carolina Orloff is an independent scholar working on research projects in the UK and in Argentina.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aPolitics in literature. 0aShort stories, Argentine. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aModern Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aCollage Books.  aCortázar's Writings.  aCuban Revolution.  aNovels.  aPolitical Representation.  aPolitical Writer.  aSocialism.  aThematic Thread.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782041368423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782041368/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles